  "texts": [
    "Naturally, π i are vector fields and f i are scalar fields.Definition 1.2 (Lipschitz solutions).",
    "Given a function ρ ∈ L ∞ (Q), a sequence of Lipschitz maps f i: Q → R and π i: Q → R d is called a Lipschitz solution to (1.3) (with the right hand side ρ) if i max{Lip(f i), ∥f i ∥ ∞ } d j=1 Lip(π j i) < ∞,(1.4)and (1.3) holds with absolute convergence in L ∞ (Q).Note that the estimate (1.4) immediately implies that the sum on the left hand side of (1.3) converges absolutely in L ∞.We now continue by defining three notions of non-regularity which we will study.",
    "It is the case that in order to resolve Conjecture 1.1, we only need to consider one of these notions (strong Lipschitz non-regularity), however, it is very instructive to discuss all three.",
    "Definition 1.3.",
    "(1) We say that the prescribed Jacobian equation has weak Lipschitz nonregularity if there exists some ρ ∈ L ∞ (Q) for which there does not exists a Lipschitz vector field π solving the equation (1.1) in the sense of equality almost everywhere."
